<h2>
    Gear &amp; Tactics for Steelhead
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Gear:</strong> Medium-heavy spinning rods (9–10 ft) or 7–8 wt fly rods. Use 12–20 lb braid with fluoro leaders or sink-tip lines if fly fishing.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Techniques:</strong>
        <ul>
            <li>
                Drift fish with roe, yarnies, or cured eggs.
            </li>
            <li>
                Plunk plugs like Spin‑N‑Glos or Kwikfish near eddies and current seams.
            </li>
            <li>
                Use spinners and spoons from boats in deeper flows.
            </li>
            <li>
                For fly gear, swing egg or leech patterns near tailouts.
            </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Access &amp; Platform Options
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>Bank Fishing:</strong> Carver Park, Eagle Creek, Oxbow Park, Dodge Park, Meldrum Bar, Sauvie sandy beaches, Government Island for easy shore access.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Drift Boats/Kayak:</strong> Available on Sandy and Clackamas rivers. Feldheimer’s Road, McIver, Barton, Carver, Riverside, and Clackamette Parks offer launches.&nbsp;
    </li>
</ul>
<h2>
    Licensing &amp; Regulations
</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        Oregon anglers must carry a <strong>valid fishing license</strong> (ages 12+) and a <strong>Combined Angling Tag</strong> for steelhead.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Columbia River Basin Endorsement</strong> required when fishing tributaries like McKenzie or Columbia for steelhead.
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>Retention Rules:</strong> Hatchery steelhead (adipose‑clipped) allowed—wild fish must be released. Daily bag limits and season months vary—always check current ODFW regulations.
    </li>
</ul>
